Class BaseFile

  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    File, Folder, Shortcut
    public abstract class BaseFile
extends BaseObject
    A base type to describe a file object, e.g. a text file on file system

    Java class for BaseFile complex type.

    The following schema fragment specifies the expected content contained within this class. 

     <complexType name="BaseFile">
   <complexContent>
     <extension base="{event-logging:3}BaseObject">
       <sequence>
         <element name="Path" type="{http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema}string" minOccurs="0"/>
         <element name="Created" type="{event-logging:3}DateTime" minOccurs="0"/>
         <element name="Modified" type="{event-logging:3}DateTime" minOccurs="0"/>
         <element name="Accessed" type="{event-logging:3}DateTime" minOccurs="0"/>
         <element name="Size" type="{http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema}nonNegativeInteger" minOccurs="0"/>
         <element name="Media" type="{event-logging:3}Media" minOccurs="0"/>
         <element name="Hash" type="{event-logging:3}Hash" maxOccurs="unbounded" minOccurs="0"/>
         <element name="Data" type="{event-logging:3}Data" maxOccurs="unbounded" minOccurs="0"/>
       </sequence>
     </extension>
   </complexContent>
 </complexType>

      • getHash

        public java.util.List<Hash> getHash()
        Describes the output of a hash function and the type of has function used.

        Gets the value of the hash property.

        This accessor method returns a reference to the live list, not a snapshot. Therefore any modification you make to the returned list will be present inside the JAXB object. This is why there is not a set method for the hash property.

        For example, to add a new item, do as follows: 

            getHash().add(newItem);

        Objects of the following type(s) are allowed in the list Hash
